Oxygen vacancy pairs have been suggested to play a role in the reduction of NO molecules on ceria and for the oxidation processes of reducible rare-earth oxides. The formation energy of the oxygen vacancy pairs and the changes in the structural and electronic properties of the ceria (110) surface with oxygen vacancy pairs are investigated using density-functional theory (DFT + U) methodology within the generalized gradient approximation. It is found that the excess electrons localize on the Ce ions neighbouring the vacancies, and the most stable structure for the oxygen vacancy pairs on the ceria (110) surface is at next-nearest-neighbour site. 2009 Elsevier B.V. All rights reserved.
1. Introduction
Ceria is one of the most interesting oxides industrially because it can readily create oxygen vacancies and whereby Ce4+ ions are reduced to Ce3+. This property gives ceria its high oxygen stor- age capacity as well as its catalytic properties; both aspects make ceria an important component of, for example, the three-way cat- alyst converter (TWC) which is used to reduce the amount of toxic species in automobile exhausts [13]. Recently, high-resolution structural information concerning oxygen vacancies on ceria sur- faces has been reported. Thus, from scanning tunneling microscope (STM) experiments, analysed with the help of density functional theory (DFT) calculations, Esch et al. have reported that the oxy- gen vacancies on reduced CeO2(111) surfaces form linear vacancy clusters [4]. Torbrugge et al. have found evidence of linear patterns of sub-surface oxygen vacancies for reduced CeO2(111) surfaces,using atomic resolution dynamic force microscopy [5]. Ultraviolet photoemission spectroscopy (UPS) and X-ray photoelectron spec- * Corresponding author. Tel.: +86 373 3329346. ** Corresponding author. Tel.: +46 (0) 18 471 37 67.
