Moreover, two NO molecules adsorbed on a reduced ceria (110) surface, O-ends down at two neighboring oxygen vacancies, their N-ends were found to form a strong NN bond with little or no barrier [11]. This is an intermediate step towards release of free N2, a reaction which is calculated to be strongly thermodynami- cally driven.
The clustering properties (e.g. the pair association) of oxygen vacancies thus have special implications for the oxidation of NO molecules on the ceria surfaces. In this Letter we present a com- prehensive DFT + U investigation of the (110) surface of ceria for different oxygen vacancy pairs: nearest neighbors, next-nearest neighbors, etc. The goal of this Letter is to find the most fa- vorable geometric configuration of oxygen vacancy pairs on ceria (110) surface. Both experiments and calculations show that the (111) surface is the most stable ceria surface; the (110) surface is thus metastable. This is especially interesting for catalytic pur- poses since the latter can therefore be expected to be more active than the former. Moreover, both force-field based [12] and DFT+ U [13] studies have suggested that surface oxygen vacancies are more stable on the (110) surface compared to those on the (111) surface.
For a single oxygen vacancy on the ceria (111) or the ce- ria (110) surface, many theoretical investigations, with many dif- ferent methods, have been reported in the literature. Force-field based methods as well as quantum-mechanical periodic DFT cal- culations or wave function-based calculations have thus been used to elucidate surface structure, electronic band structure, electron localization, surface dynamics, defect stability, etc., of the oxy- gen vacancy on these surfaces [1417]. In addition, several papers have appeared with a focus on methodological aspects relating to the calculation of strongly correlated systems such as reduced ce- ria. We do not list all these references here, but rather refer to Refs. [1417] as being periodic DFT calculations of particular rel- evance for the current study. References within these publications together provide an extensive list.
