2. Model and calculation methods
2.1. Description of the model systems
Bulk crystalline CeO2 has the fluorite structure. Reference cal- culations for bulk CeO2 were performed for a 12-atom unit cell,which was optimized with respect to both the cell parameter and the atomic positions, until the force on each atom was less than
0.02 eV/Å and the stress tensor on the cell less than 0.1 GPa.
Our calculations gave an equilibrium lattice parameter of 5.480 Å,which is close to the experimental value of 5.411 Å [18].The CeO2(110) surface system was modeled as a stack of (neu- tral) CeO2 layers in a supercell containing 108 atoms, out of which two neutral O atoms were subsequently removed from the top layer, in different geometrical constellations. In order to dimin- ish the interaction between the defects and their periodic images,a large lateral cell was used, namely p(3 × 3), but instead the slab was made only 4 layers thick. The two bottom layers were fixed at their bulk positions, while the positions of the ions in the two up- per layers were fully optimized (under the restriction of fixed cell parameters). A vacuum layer of 15 Å was introduced to separate the films. The side view of the unreduced CeO2(110) slab model is shown in Fig. 1(a), and the top view in Fig. 1(b). The latter figure also defines the labels of the various oxygen vacancy pairs exam- ined in this Letter. The (3 × 3) surface expansion ensures enough separations between defects (e.g., 11.62 Å between single vacan- cies; 8.36 Å between the closest vacancy pairs). Test calculations using a thicker slab (a 5-layer slab) showed that the results are reasonably converged, e.g. the single vacancy formation energy for a 5-layer slab has a small difference (0.1 eV) as compared with that for a 4-layer slab. Most importantly, the relative stability of different vacancy patterns are almost the same and the trend is not changed.
2.2. Calculations
Spin-polarized KohnSham density functional theory calcula- tions were performed using the Vienna ab initio simulation package (VASP) [19,20]. The valence electronic states were thus expanded in a basis of plane waves. The projector-augmented wave (PAW) method [21] of Blchl, as implemented in VASP, was used for the treatment of the core electrons, and the cerium 5s, 5p, 5d, 4 f , and 6s electrons, the oxygen 2s and 2p were treated as valence elec- trons. The electron exchange and correlation were treated within the generalized gradient approximation (GGA) using the Perdew BurkeErnzerhof (PBE) functional. DFT with the inclusion of on-site Coulomb interaction (the DFT + U method) [22,23] was chosen as our computational approach, due to the inability of GGA-DFT to describe the Ce4 f electronic states which result from formation of oxygen vacancies in ceria [16,24,25]. In the DFT + U method,a Hubbard parameter, U, is introduced for the Ce4 f electrons to describe the on-site Coulomb interaction; this helps to remove the self-interaction error and improves the description of correlation effects. Some authors have already described how the value of U is fitted against experimental results for correctly describing the properties of both the CeO2 and partially reduced ceria (CeO2x) 2788
