E v = E(v) E(CeO2) + 1/2E(O2),(2) E vpair = E(vi, v j) E(CeO2) + E(O2).
(3) E(CeO2) is the total energy per supercell of the stoichiometric system. E(v) is the total energy of the reduced supercell with one O vacancy in the surface layer. E(vi, v j) is the total energy of the reduced supercell with two O vacancies (at site i and site j, re- spectively). E(O2) is the total energy for the ground state of an optimized oxygen molecule in the gas phase. By substituting (2) and (3) into (1), we can write Epairing as Epairing = E(vi, v j) 2E(v) + E(CeO2).
(4) Thus, a negative value for Epairing means that the formation of an O vacancy pair is more favorable than the formation of two iso- lated O vacancies, and a positive value means that vacancy pairing is unfavorable.
3. Results and discussion
3.1. Single oxygen vacancy
3.1.1. Energetics and geometric structure
As a reference for the oxygen vacancy pairs, firstly, the ce- ria (110) surface with a single vacancy was studied. A single oxy- gen vacancy was created by removing an oxygen atom from the relaxed stoichiometric CeO2(110)p(3× 3) surface. The fully relaxed atomic structures at the DFT + U level are showed in Fig. 2(a) and (b), together with the distribution of extra electrons on two Ce ions neighboring the vacancy which corresponds two reduced Ce ions (denoted as Ce3+) and will be discussed below. The for- mation energy (E v) for a single surface oxygen vacancy calcu- lated using Eq. (2) is 2.10 eV, which is close to our former result (2.30 eV) [27]. The small difference is probably caused by the different supercells used in our two calculations (in the present study we have a larger surface cell, i.e. lower vacancy concentra- tion, and a thinner slab), and by the different cutoff energies used for the plane wave expansion (350 eV vs. 408 eV). It has been re- ported [14,25] that on the ceria (111) surface, the subsurface O vacancy is more stable than the surface vacancy. For comparison,we checked the subsurface vacancy and found a structure which is much less stable than the surface vacancy on ceria (110) surface,e.g. the formation energy of a subsurface oxygen vacancy is higher by 1.44 eV than that of a surface oxygen vacancy. Therefore, the oxygen vacancy is preferred to be created on the top layer of the ceria (110) surface. It is obviously an approximation not to allow relaxations in the third layer; however we expect them to be quite small. We have checked with the current 4 layer slabs for allow- ing the 3rd layer relaxations. The results are slightly different from those presented for the case with the 3rd layer fixed, e.g., the sin- gle oxygen vacancy formation energy is lowered by about 0.07 eV.
It is found that the formation of a surface oxygen vacancy in- duces very large relaxations, similar to the features that have been found in our previous paper for the CeO2(110)p(2 × 2) [27]. As shown in Fig. 2(a) and (b), at the defective ceria (110) surface with an oxygen vacancy, the closest surface O neighbor on the left side of the vacancy moves toward the vacancy by about 0.26 Å. This
