3.1.2. Electronic structure
Reduction strongly modifies the electronic structure of the ce- ria surface. The total density of states (TDOS) for the ceria (110) surface with a single-oxygen vacancy is shown in Fig. 2(c). Similar to experimental observations [6,7] and DFT + U results in the lit- erature [13,27], a new DOS peak near the Fermi level appears in the O2pCe4 f gap. The electron density of these gap states is dis- played in Fig. 2(a) and (b). The localization of excess electrons on the two cerium sites neighboring the oxygen vacancy site in the surface layer is clearly seen, showing that the gap states found in Fig. 2(c) arise from the formation of two reduced Ce3+ ions. Again,these findings are consistent with experimental results [6,7]. The spin density (spin-up electron density minus spin-down electron density; not shown here) looks very similar to the electron den- sity of the gap states [as displayed in Fig. 2(a) and (b)] and shows that the defective (110) surface is ferromagnetic with all the spin moments are parallel aligned.
The partial density of state (PDOS) (not shown here) shows that the gap state peaks are almost pure Ce4 f states. We also performed a Bader type analysis [30] of the electron density cor- responding to the gap states and found that there are about 0.98 excess electrons localized on each of the reduced Ce3+ ions in the surface layer, similar to our former results (0.93) [27].
