3.2.2. Electronic structure
When two neutral oxygen atoms are removed from the ce- ria (110) surface, four electrons are left behind. The surface relax- ation discussed above occurs as a consequence of the loss of the O atoms and the redistribution of the excess electrons. In this sec- tion we will discuss the details of the electronic structure and the electron distribution, with special emphasis on the P15 structure.
The total density of states for the P15 structure is shown in Fig. 4(b). Similar to the single-vacancy case, a new peak is seen to appear between the top of the valence band and the bottom of the unoccupied Ce4 f states. A Bader type analysis [30] of the charge density corresponding to these gap states reveals that four electrons are localized on the four Ce ions neighboring the oxy- gen vacancy pairs (about 0.99 excess electrons on each Ce ion; see Fig. 4(a)). A PDOS analysis shows that the gap states peak consists almost exclusively of Ce4 f electrons.
Now let us analyze the physical origin of why the P15 oxygen vacancy pair structure on the ceria (110) surface is the most favor- able. The distribution of the excess electron density (corresponding to the gap states) for all the other vacancy pair constellations stud- ied here are shown in Fig. 5. There would be two main factors that affect the formation energy of the oxygen vacancy pair. On the one hand, it can be seen clearly that the structures (e.g. P12, P13, P14, P16) that have some excess electrons localized on one or more Ce ions on the subsurface layer (e.g., the Ce cations with the dashed circles in Fig. 5) have higher formation energies for the oxygen vacancy pair, while the structures (e.g. P15, P17, P37) with all the excess electrons localized on the surface layer have relatively lower formation energies for the oxygen vacancy pair.
It is known that the reduced cerium cations (Ce3+) are larger in size than the Ce4+, therefore the creation of Ce3+ in the sublayer would cost more energy (for the structure adaptation for the larger Ce3+ cations) than in the top layer. Furthermore, the formation of the vacancies provides extra space for accommodating the bigger Ce3+, which makes the excess electrons tend to localize on the Ce ions neighboring the vacancies. We will call this factor the struc- tural adaptation. On the other hand, the Ce cations with excess electrons would tend to be further apart because of the Coulomb repulsion. If the creation of oxygen vacancy pairs results in Ce3+ cations that are far apart, the formation energy would be lower because of the lower Coulomb repulsion. We call this factor as the electronic adaptation. By inspecting the three structures with relatively lower formation energies, i.e., the P15 (Fig. 4(a)), P17 (Fig. 5(e)) and P37 (Fig. 5(f)), it is found that their excess elec- trons are localized on two Ce3+ pairs. The intra-pair distances (the CeCe distances within a pair of Ce3+) are similar (4.24 Å, 4.21 Å,
4.23 Å), while the inter-pair distances (the CeCe distances be-
