The larger inter-pair distances in the P15 structure as compared with others makes it more favorable. Both the structural adap- tation and electronic adaptation are decisive for the final geo- metric structure of the oxygen vacancy pairs. There should be a balance between the two factors (e.g. structural adaptation and electronic adaptation). On the one hand, the structural adapta- tion makes the excess electrons localize close to the vacancies, on the other hand, the electronic adaptation makes the excess elec- trons depart away as far as possible.
3.2.3. Implication for NO reduction
As mentioned in the introduction section, Daturi et al. [10] have proposed a mechanism for the dissociation of NO on ceria whereby two NO molecules adsorbed on neighboring oxygen va- cancies react to give dinitrogen. Using DFT calculations, Yang et al. performed a preliminary examination of this idea by considering two NO molecules adsorbed on a preformed nearest neighboring oxygen vacancy pairs [11]. In the present study, we found that the most stable configuration of an oxygen vacancy pair on the ce- ria (110) is the P15 pattern (the next nearest neighboring pair) instead of the nearest neighboring pairs. This result, especially if it can be confirmed by experiment in the future, will be impor- tant for the understanding of the dissociation mechanism of NO molecules on ceria. To this end, test calculations for the adsorp- tion of two NO molecules on the most stable di-vacancy surface (P15) were performed. It is found that there is no clear tendency of forming an NN bond. Instead, the NO molecules were adsorbed above the vacancies with their NO bonds lying almost parallel to the surface O rows as shown in Fig. 6(a) and (b). The adsorbed NO molecules bind with the surface Ce3+ ions neighboring the vacan- cies through their both ends and the NO bonds are stretched by about 0.1 Å as compared with the calculated value for the free NO.The bond lengths are shown in Fig. 6(b). The gap states [as shown in the DOS plots in Fig. 6(c)] and the corresponding electron dis- tribution [Fig. 6(b)] show clearly that bonds formed between NO molecules and the surface Ce3+ ions. Indeed, Bader charge anal- ysis [30] shows that the adsorbed NO molecules get about 0.65 electrons each. Since the mechanism for the dissociation of NO on ceria proposed by Daturi et al. [10] depends closely on the for- mation of neighboring vacancies, some factors (e.g. doping with metal atoms) would be needed to enhance the formation of near- est neighboring vacancy pairs or clusters. Further studies are un- dertaken to verify this.
4. Conclusions
The DFT + U formalism has been used to study oxygen va- cancy pairs defects on the (110) surface of ceria. Geometrically,it is found that the most favorable oxygen vacancy pair is the next nearest neighbor pattern (i.e., the P15 pattern in our deno- tation), instead of the nearest neighbor pattern. Two main factors,i.e. structural adaptation and electronic adaptation, are found to be decisive for the formation energy and the association energy of the oxygen vacancy pairs and therefore determine final geomet- ric structure of the oxygen vacancy pairs. The electronic properties of the oxygen vacancy pairs were studied through the density of states and the charge density analyses. For the most stable oxygen vacancy pair pattern (the P15 pattern), extra electron localization is found on four neighboring Ce4+ ions, which are reduced to Ce3+.
For some of the other oxygen vacancy pairs examined, the electron localization is clearly different from the sum of two isolated va- cancies, and often involves the creation of Ce3+ ions in the second atomic layer. The results in the present work will be important for understanding the mechanisms about the dissociation of NO molecules on ceria.


